1)b)Write about transformation throughout the novella.
You should consider:
the ways that characters transform
how transformation is presented.
Dickens presents transformation in the novella using the character of Scrooge. Through
Scrooge’s progression from a hardened miser into a joyful man who embraces the Christmas
spirit, Dickens shows that transformations are positive experiences that benet the person
undergoing the transformation as well as those around them. This is shown through Dickens’s
use of imagery as well as Scrooge’s language. Additionally, revisited events and contrasting
language make transformations all the more powerful for the reader.
Dickens uses language relating to childhood to show the extent of Scrooge’s
transformation. At the end of the novella, Scrooge is no longer “morose” like he was at
the beginning, but is instead “as merry as a school-boy”. Alongside showing that Scrooge’s
newfound happiness is as pure as that of a child, this simile could suggest that Scrooge
has transformed into being receptive to education by the spirits and open to changing his
behaviour. Furthermore, Scrooge refers to himself as “quite a baby”, which has connotations
of rebirth and the ability to begin a new life. This implies that Scrooge’s transformation is so
complete that it can allow him to start life afresh as if he were a child.
Scrooge’s language also demonstrates the extent of his transformation. In ChapterOne,
Scrooge refers to those who enjoy Christmas as “fools”: this derogatory term illustrates his
condescending attitude towards the festive season. However, in Chapter Five, he uses
exclamations such as “Whoop!” and “A merry Christmas to everybody!”, which make his
excitement clear. The transformation of Scrooge’s speech has a powerful effect on the reader,
as it emphasises the strength of his Christmas spirit and how drastically he has changed.
